<item>
            <title>[GROOVY-5809] .groovy files on the classpath don&apos;t work if the absolute path contains non-latin characters</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-5809</link>
                <project id="12318123" key="GROOVY">Groovy</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;If you have a .groovy file on the classpath when running a groovy script, imports of the classpath located file from the main script (or other places) only work when the absolute path to the .groovy file being imported doesn&apos;t contain non-latin characters.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It doesn&apos;t seem to make any difference whether or not the file to be imported is in the default package (top level) or not.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This problem is easy to reproduce. Attached is zip file with a groovy script and a single dependency in a subdirectory called &apos;test+test&apos;. If you unzip this and cd to the subdirectory and run:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;groovy -cp . Script.groovy&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;... it will fail. If you cd up a level and change the name of the directory from &apos;test+test&apos; to &apos;test&apos; then cd back into test and re-run it, it will work.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>Verified on Windows and Linux</environment>
        <key id="12816627">GROOVY-5809</key>
